Credit Risk Modeling¶

A project realised by Dr-eng.: Khalifa Mejbri, Consultant in Engineering, Data Science and Machine Learning.¶

Part 2. Model Development and Performance Evaluation¶

In the second part of the credit risk modeling project, we extend the analytical scope beyond Probability of Default (PD) to also include Loss Given Default (LGD) and Exposure at Default (EAD), forming the three pillars of Expected Loss (EL) modeling as required under Basel II/III frameworks. This integrated risk modeling approach allows for a comprehensive and quantitative estimation of credit risk.

Objectives:¶

  • Develop supervised learning models to estimate:

    • PD (Probability of Default) – likelihood that a borrower will default.
    • LGD (Loss Given Default) – percentage of the exposure that will be lost if a default occurs.
    • EAD (Exposure at Default) – total value the lender is exposed to at the time of default.

  • Use the modeled components to compute the Expected Loss using the formula:

                            EL = PD × LGD × EAD

Key steps in this part:¶

  • Model Training: Train separate models for PD, LGD, and EAD using relevant subsets of the data and appropriate algorithms (e.g., logistic regression for PD, linear regression or beta regression for LGD, and regression models for EAD).
  • Feature Selection & Transformation: Tailor features for each target variable with domain-informed engineering.
  • Validation: Evaluate model performance using relevant metrics:
    • PD: AUC-ROC, KS-statistic, confusion matrix
    • LGD & EAD: R², RMSE, MAE, residual analysis
  • EL Computation: Integrate the model outputs to estimate expected loss at loan or portfolio level.
  • Risk Insights: Interpret models to provide actionable insights for risk-based pricing, provisioning, and capital allocation.

This part translates raw and engineered features into predictive models that can estimate future losses with business relevance and regulatory alignment.

3. Selecting the Reference Categories and Splitting Data¶

For credit risk modeling using a logistic regression with WoE-transformed variables, the category with WoE equal to zero can be considered a reference category, as it reflects average risk and serves as a neutral benchmark for interpreting the model’s coefficients.

Conceptually Justified Because:¶

  • WoE = 0 implies that the proportion of good and bad loans in that category matches the overall average.
  • This makes it a neutral benchmark for comparing the riskiness of other categories.
  • Since WoE is already a log-odds transformation, logistic regression coefficients become additive adjustments to the log-odds based on deviations from the average.

Interpretation Tip:¶

  • If a bin has WoE = 0, its effect on the log-odds is zero — hence, it contributes nothing additional to the predicted default risk.
  • Other bins will have positive or negative contributions relative to that neutral bin.

II. PD Model Estimation¶

A. Logistic Regression Model with P-Values¶

Metric Function¶

Let's create a function to calculate and print the classification report and confusion matrix so that we don't have to rewrite the same code repeatedly for each model.

In [17]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cf, group_names=None, categories='auto', count=True, percent=True, cbar=True, xyticks=True, 
                          xyplotlabels=True, sum_stats=True, figsize=None, cmap='Blues', title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''
    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.3%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])

    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False

    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf, annot=box_labels, fmt="", cmap=cmap, cbar=cbar, xticklabels=categories, yticklabels=categories)

    if title:
        plt.title(title)
In [18]:
# Creating metric function
def metrics_score(y_true, y_pred, y_proba):
    """
    Evaluates model performance using various classification metrics, prioritizing recall and AUC-ROC for fraud detection.

    Parameters:
    y_true (array-like): True labels.
    y_pred (array-like): Predicted labels.
    y_proba (array-like): Predicted probabilities for the positive class.

    Returns:
    None (Prints metrics, confusion matrix, and classification report).
    """
    print("\nModel Performance Metrics:")
    
    # Recall (Priority for fraud detection)
    recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Recall (Priority Metric): {recall:.4f}")

    # AUC-ROC Score (Priority for fraud detection)
    auc_roc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_proba)
    print(f"AUC-ROC Score (Priority Metric): {auc_roc:.4f}")

    # Accuracy
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")

    # Precision
    precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")

    # F1 Score
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")
    
    # Detailed Classification Report
    print("\nClassification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred))

    # Confusion Matrix
    print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    labels = ['True Positive','False Negative','False Positive','True Negative']
    categories = [ 'Good loan','Bad loan']
    make_confusion_matrix(cm, group_names=labels, categories=categories, cmap='Blues')

Build a Logistic Regression Model with P-Values¶

In [19]:
# P values for sklearn logistic regression.

# Class to display p-values for logistic regression in sklearn.

from sklearn import linear_model
import scipy.stats as stat

class LogisticRegression_with_p_values:
    
    def __init__(self,*args,**kwargs):
        self.model = linear_model.LogisticRegression(*args,**kwargs)

    def fit(self,X,y):
        self.model.fit(X,y)
        
        #### Get p-values for the fitted model ####
        denom = (2.0 * (1.0 + np.cosh(self.model.decision_function(X))))
        denom = np.tile(denom,(X.shape[1],1)).T
        F_ij = np.dot((X / denom).T,X) ## Fisher Information Matrix
        # Add small identity matrix to ensure invertibility
        F_ij = F_ij + 1e-6 * np.eye(F_ij.shape[0])
        Cramer_Rao = np.linalg.inv(F_ij) ## Inverse Information Matrix
        sigma_estimates = np.sqrt(np.diagonal(Cramer_Rao))
        z_scores = self.model.coef_[0] / sigma_estimates # z-score for eaach model coefficient
        p_values = [stat.norm.sf(abs(x)) * 2 for x in z_scores] ### two tailed test for p-values
        
        self.coef_ = self.model.coef_
        self.intercept_ = self.model.intercept_
        self.p_values = p_values

 # Predict methods
    def predict(self, X):
        return self.model.predict(X)

    def predict_proba(self, X):
        return self.model.predict_proba(X)

# Creates a new column in the dataframe, called 'Coefficients',
# with row values the transposed coefficients from the 'LogisticRegression' object.
summary_table.index = summary_table.index + 1
# Increases the index of every row of the dataframe with 1.
summary_table.loc[0] = ['Intercept', reg1.intercept_[0]]
# Assigns values of the row with index 0 of the dataframe.
summary_table = summary_table.sort_index()
# Sorts the dataframe by index.

Comprehensive Feature Selection Analysis for Credit Risk Model Refinement¶

1. Key Criteria for Feature Retention/Dropping¶

  • Statistical Significance (p-value < 0.05): Prioritize features with strong evidence against the null hypothesis.
  • Magnitude of Coefficient: Large absolute coefficients indicate strong predictive power (e.g., debt_settlement_flag:Y).
  • Business Logic: Retain features aligned with domain knowledge (e.g., FICO scores, loan terms).
  • Collinearity Check: Exclude redundant features (e.g., multiple FICO-related bins with overlapping effects).

A complete list of features to drop based on high p-values (> 0.05), near-zero coefficients, or redundancy, formatted for easy implementation:

Interpretations:¶

This is a comprehensive logistic regression result for a credit risk model using binned features and WoE-style transformations. Below is a structured interpretation of key findings, broken down into:

1. General Observations¶

  • High significance: Many predictors have very small p-values (p < 0.05) indicating strong evidence against the null hypothesis (coefficient ≠ 0).
  • Well-behaved coefficients: Signs are generally interpretable (e.g., higher delinquency increases risk, more principal paid reduces risk).
  • Some redundancy remains: Some features (e.g., fico_range_high, mo_sin_rcnt_tl) have non-significant p-values, suggesting further pruning may be possible.
  • Dominant features: A few predictors have very large absolute coefficients, meaning they strongly drive the model's decision.

2. Most Influential Variables (Statistically Significant & Large Coefficients)¶

These variables are both statistically significant (p < 0.05) and have large coefficients, so they dominate model predictions:

  • principal_paid_ratio:<=0.3 (coef = +4.21): Customers who paid little principal are highly risky.
  • principal_paid_ratio:0.3-0.45 (coef = +3.18): Similar implication as above.
  • principal_paid_ratio:0.45-0.6 (coef = +2.46): Gradually less risky as ratio increases.
  • principal_paid_ratio:0.6-1 (coef = -5.87): Strongly negative — implies lower risk.
  • last_pymnt_amnt:>2600 (coef = -4.2 to -4.6): Higher recent payments = lower risk.
  • out_prncp:>0 (coef = +7.34): Indicates loan is still outstanding — very risky.
  • debt_settlement_flag:Y (coef = +8.05): Very strong positive — major red flag for default.
  • term:60 (coef = +0.50): Longer-term loans are riskier.
  • months_since_last_credit_pull:48-55 (coef = +1.68): Suggests risk increases with delay in credit activity.
  • months_since_last_credit_pull:>55 (coef = -0.84): This negative value is interesting — could be statistical artifact or cohort behavior.

Recommendation: Use these features for risk scoring, and possibly rule-based early warning systems.

3. Moderately Predictive Financial Ratios¶

  • dti:20-30 (coef = +0.11): Higher debt-to-income increases risk.
  • total_bal_ex_mort_to_inc:0.4-0.8 (coef = +0.05): Slight increase in risk with more total balance.
  • rev_to_il_limit_ratio:>3.5 (coef = +0.12): High revolving to installment limit ratio is a risk flag.
  • avg_cur_bal:30-50k (coef = -0.11): Higher current balance could imply financial capacity.
  • total_il_high_credit_limit:30-35k (coef = -0.20): Access to installment credit may reduce risk.

4. Categorical Indicators of Risk¶

  • home_ownership:RENT_OTHER_NONE_ANY (coef = +0.07): Renters slightly riskier.
  • verification_status:Not Verified (coef = -0.11): Lower verification is a strong risk signal.
  • application_type:Joint App (coef = -0.35): Joint applications are less risky.
  • emp_length_int:10 (coef = +0.17): More employment years increases chance of repayment.
  • addr_state:MT_SC (coef = -0.18): Some geographies have distinct risk profiles.
  • inq_last_6mths:>=4 (coef = -0.11): Many inquiries may suggest desperate borrowing or active credit seeking.

5. Variables with High p-values (p > 0.05)¶

These are not statistically significant and may be pruned in future modeling iterations:

  • grade:A, grade:G, grade:E, etc. — surprisingly many grade levels are insignificant.
  • annual_inc:20K-30K, 40K-50K — not significant despite logical relevance.
  • delinq_2yrs:>=7, inq_last_6mths:>=4, fico_range_high:700-795 — classic credit risk features, but not significant here (possibly due to multicollinearity).
  • mo_sin_rcnt_tl:* and mo_sin_rcnt_rev_tl_op:* — mostly insignificant.

Recommendation: Consider removing or combining categories in future iterations to simplify the model without losing predictive power.

Recommendations:¶

Model Refinement¶

  • 1. Drop high p-value features unless theory strongly supports them:
    • Very high p-values (e.g., > 0.3).
    • Low coefficients.
    • No practical interpretation.
  • 2. Regularization (e.g., L1 logistic regression) can help enforce sparsity automatically.
  • 3. Group similar features: If multiple related bins (e.g., income levels) are all insignificant, collapse them into fewer bins.

Business Actionables¶

  • 1. Flag high-risk accounts:
    • principal_paid_ratio <= 0.6
    • out_prncp > 0
    • debt_settlement_flag = Y
    • Low recent payments (last_pymnt_amnt <= 600)
  • 2. Enhance credit policy:
    • Tighten criteria for long loan terms (term:60)
    • Investigate joint applications with lower risk
    • Focus on underperforming geographies (addr_state effects)

Model Use Case:¶

This model is highly suitable for:

  • Credit scoring
  • Portfolio segmentation
  • Loss forecasting
  • Collections strategy

Interpretations:¶

The logistic regression model shows excellent performance on both the training and test datasets. Here's a detailed interpretation of each part:

Accuracy and AUC-ROC Scores¶

  • Accuracy: The model correctly classifies 98.6% of the loans, both in training and test data. This is very high, indicating strong predictive power.
  • AUC-ROC Score: Near-perfect scores (~0.998) suggest your model has an excellent ability to distinguish between defaulters (class 1) and non-defaulters (class 0). It’s one of the most reliable indicators of classification performance, especially for imbalanced datasets.

Classification Report Interpretation¶

For both training and test data:

  • Class 0 (Non-Default Loans)
    • Precision ≈ 0.99: When the model predicts a loan will not default, it is correct 99% of the time.
    • Recall ≈ 1.00: The model correctly identifies nearly all actual non-defaulters.
    • F1-score ≈ 0.99: High balance between precision and recall.
  • Class 1 (Default Loans)
    • Precision ≈ 0.98: When the model predicts a default, it's correct 98% of the time.
    • Recall ≈ 0.95: It captures 95% of actual defaulters — this is crucial in risk modeling.
    • F1-score ≈ 0.97: Very strong combined measure of precision and recall.

Confusion matrix¶

  • Terminology Reminder:

    • True Positive (TP): Correctly predicted non-defaulters (class 0).
    • False Negative (FN): Misclassified actual non-defaulters as defaulters.
    • False Positive (FP): Misclassified actual defaulters as non-defaulters — riskier in credit modeling.
    • True Negative (TN): Correctly predicted defaulters (class 1).

  • Training Dataset Confusion Matrix Interpretation:

    • Very low FN and FP: excellent at catching both non-defaulters and defaulters.
    • Small number of defaulters are misclassified as safe, which is important to monitor.

  • Testing Dataset Confusion Matrix Interpretation

    • Near-identical performance as the training set → confirms model generalization.
    • False Positive Rate (1.05%) is very low but still needs attention since these represent loans incorrectly approved.

  • Key Takeaways:

    • FPs (1.05%) are crucial: even though small, these are loans you thought were safe but will default, leading to financial loss.
    • FNs (0.35%) represent rejected safe borrowers — better than approving risky ones, but may reduce customer satisfaction.
    • High TP (78%) and TN (20%) coverage shows the model is well-balanced.
    • Consistency between training and testing confusion matrices shows minimal overfitting.

Conclusion¶

  • These model generalizes extremely well: train and test scores are virtually identical — no overfitting.
  • Both default and non-default classes are well-handled, with only a small drop in recall for defaulters (from ~95%).
  • he model is highly reliable for production use in credit risk modeling.

Interpretations:¶

The feature importance analysis based on the logistic regression results. The model coefficients represent the log-odds impact of each feature on the probability of default. The larger the absolute value, the more influential the feature is. Positive coefficients increase the risk of default, while negative coefficients reduce it.

Top Drivers of Default Risk (High Absolute Coefficients)¶

  • 1. debt_settlement_flag:Y (coef = +8.05): If a borrower has a history of debt settlement, the odds of default increase sharply. This is the strongest risk indicator.
  • 2. out_prncp:>0 (coef = +7.34): Borrowers with outstanding principal are much more likely to default — makes sense, as they haven't repaid the loan.
  • 3. principal_paid_ratio:0.6-1 (coef = −5.87): Borrowers who have paid 60% to 100% of the principal are significantly less likely to default.
  • 4. last_fico_range_high:<=520 (coef = +5.86): Very low FICO score is strongly associated with high default risk.
  • 5. last_fico_range_high:520–550 (coef = +5.14): Similar to above — still a very poor FICO group.
  • 6. last_pymnt_amnt:>10000 (coef = −4.65): Large recent payment is a strong signal of good repayment behavior.
  • 7. last_fico_range_high:550–580 (coef = +4.62): Poor credit score group; still high risk.
  • 8. principal_paid_ratio:<=0.3 (coef = +4.22): Borrowers who have paid off very little of their loan are highly risky.
  • 9. last_pymnt_amnt:2600–10000 (coef = −4.20): Medium-large recent payments still reduce risk considerably.
  • 10. last_fico_range_high:580–610 (coef = +3.84): Slightly better but still subprime score — increases risk.

Features that REDUCE Default Probability (Negative Coefficients)¶

These features have negative coefficients, meaning they are associated with lower default odds:

  • High principal paid (e.g., principal_paid_ratio:0.6-1)
  • Large or medium recent payments (last_pymnt_amnt:>10000, 2600-10000)
  • Higher loan repayment progress overall.

Such features signal that the borrower is actively repaying and likely to complete the loan.

Features that INCREASE Default Probability (Positive Coefficients)¶

These features increase the likelihood of default:

  • Low or very low FICO scores (e.g., last_fico_range_high:<=580)
  • Outstanding loan principal (out_prncp:>0)
  • Low principal repayment (principal_paid_ratio:<=0.3)
  • Debt settlement history (debt_settlement_flag:Y)
  • Longer loan terms (term:60)
  • High loan amount brackets (loan_amnt:>=28500)

These indicators align with financial stress, poor creditworthiness, or risky loan structures.

Moderate Importance Features¶

Features like months_since_last_credit_pull, loan amount buckets, and num_bc_tl have smaller coefficients (~±0.5 to ±1.5) but still contribute meaningfully:

  • Loan_amnt:>=28500 (+1.87): Higher loan size is modestly riskier.
  • Months_since_last_credit_pull:48-55 (+1.67): Stale credit checks may correlate with higher risk.
  • term:60 (+0.50): Longer term loans are slightly riskier — more time for things to go wrong.

Overall Takeaway:¶

These model is driven strongly by:

  • Creditworthiness (FICO score ranges)
  • Repayment behavior (principal paid, last payment amount)
  • Debt status (debt settlement, outstanding principal)
  • Loan structure (loan amount, term)

These results make intuitive and financial sense, and the direction of coefficients aligns with practical credit risk reasoning.

Interpretations:¶

The Random Forest model for credit risk PD (Probability of Default) modeling shows strong and consistent performance on both the training and testing datasets. Here's a detailed interpretation of the results:

1. Priority Metrics Interpretation¶

  • AUC-ROC Score:

    • Training: 0.9974
    • Testing: 0.9970
    • Interpretation: These near-perfect scores show that the model has excellent discriminatory power — it can distinguish between defaulters and non-defaulters with very high accuracy. The small drop from train to test suggests the model generalizes well and is not overfitting.

  • Recall (Sensitivity for Class 1 - Defaulters):

    • Training: 0.9461
    • Testing: 0.9451
    • Interpretation: Around 94.5% of all actual defaulters were correctly identified. This is critical in PD modeling where missing a defaulter (false negative) is more costly than flagging a non-defaulter.

2. Overall Performance¶

  • Accuracy:
    • Training: 98.51%
    • Testing: 98.47%
    • Interpretation: The model correctly classifies almost all cases. However, since the dataset is likely imbalanced, accuracy alone isn't enough — hence your focus on recall and AUC is correct.
  • Precision:
    • Training: 98.40%
    • Testing: 98.27%
    • Interpretation: Most predicted defaulters actually are defaulters — low false positive rate. This is valuable when acting on predictions has costs (e.g., rejecting applicants).
  • F1 Score:
    • Training: 0.9647
    • Testing: 0.9635
    • Interpretation: Strong balance between precision and recall for the positive class (defaults). A stable F1 across train/test also shows good generalization.

3. Classification Report Analysis¶

  • For Class 1 (Defaulters):
    • Precision ~ 0.98
    • Recall ~ 0.95
    • F1 Score ~ 0.96
    • Interpretation: The model is excellent at identifying defaulters and maintains a low false positive rate.
  • For Class 0 (Non-defaulters):
    • Precision & Recall ~ 0.99 to 1.00
    • Interpretation: Very strong performance on the majority class, which is typical for Random Forests trained on imbalanced data if balanced carefully or with class weighting.

4. Generalization & Overfitting Check¶

  • Minimal performance drop from training to testing across all metrics.
  • Suggests the model is not overfitting, likely due to the ensemble nature of Random Forest and possible use of regularization (e.g., max depth, min samples).

5. Confusion Matrix:¶

For Training:

  • Excellent ability to detect defaulters (high TP, low FN).
  • Low false alarms (FP).
  • Indicates very strong model fit with no major overfitting (will be confirmed by test performance).

For Testing:

  • Test results closely mirror training performance — a sign of excellent generalization.
  • The balance of high TP, low FN, and moderate FP means:
    • The model captures most risky loans (defaulters),
    • Without significantly penalizing good borrowers.

Final Takeaway:

  • The model is highly effective at identifying defaulters, which is the main goal in PD modeling.
  • Low false negatives mean few defaulters will escape detection — important for managing credit risk.
  • Moderate false positives are acceptable trade-offs in exchange for high safety.
  • Consistent performance between training and testing suggests a robust and reliable model, ready for business application or regulatory consideration.

Interpretations:¶

1. Key Interpretation Principles¶

  • Feature importance scores represent the average decrease in impurity (like Gini or entropy) across all trees when a feature is used for splitting.
  • Higher importance → feature was used more often or was more effective in reducing classification error.
  • These values do not indicate direction (positive/negative) — unlike logistic regression coefficients.

2. Most Important Feature¶

  • principal_paid_ratio:0.6-1: 0.3308
  • Interpretation: Borrowers who have repaid 60–100% of the principal are a major signal for low PD (good behavior).
  • This likely helps the model distinguish “paid-up” or performing loans from those at risk.

3. Other Highly Influential Features¶

  • principal_paid_ratio:<=0.3: (0.1606) Low repayment ratio → strong indicator of high PD.
  • last_pymnt_amnt:200-600: (0.0754) Low recent payment amount — signals financial stress.
  • last_pymnt_amnt:2600-10000: (0.0646) Captures variability in payment behavior.
  • last_pymnt_amnt:>10000: (0.0443) Very high payments may indicate final payoff (low PD).
  • last_fico_range_high:<=520: (0.0398) Extremely low FICO → strongly associated with default.
  • debt_settlement_flag:Y : (0.0229) Flagged for debt settlement → risky borrower.

These features dominate the model and likely drive most of its predictive power.

4. Less Important Features¶

  • grade:A, grade:E, etc. : (~0.009–0.002) Basic risk grade matters, but less than behavioral features.
  • loan_amnt, int_rate, open_act_il, verification_status : (< 0.002) Still contribute, but less decisive than payment behavior or FICO.
  • Features with importance < 0.001 : Minimal or redundant. Could be considered for pruning or dimensionality reduction.

5. Thematic Takeaways¶

  • Behavioral variables dominate:
    • Features derived from payment behavior (last_pymnt_amnt, principal_paid_ratio) are most predictive of PD.
    • These reflect real-time financial stress or good performance.
  • FICO scores and risk flags are strong:
    • last_fico_range_high buckets and debt_settlement_flag provide key risk signals.
  • Loan terms and demographic features matter less:
    • Features like loan_amnt, term, verification_status, and int_rate play a secondary role.

C. Comparison of Logistic Regression and Random Forest models¶

We compare the Logistic Regression and Random Forest models based on the evaluation metrics, focusing on their test set performance, since this reflects generalization to unseen data.

1. Interpretation¶

  • Logistic Regression Strengths:

    • Slightly higher AUC and accuracy, indicating better overall ranking of predictions.
    • More interpretable with clear coefficients and p-values (critical in regulated credit risk modeling).
    • Lower false negatives — fewer defaulters missed.

  • Random Forest Strengths:

    • Slightly higher F1 Score and Precision, meaning it’s better at avoiding false positives while catching true defaulters.
    • Handles non-linear feature interactions without needing manual transformations.
    • Robust model that still generalizes well (no overfitting observed).

2. Recommendation¶

Since both models perform exceptionally well, and the logistic regression model gives nearly identical metrics with much better interpretability, we would recommend the Logistic Regression as a final model for PD modeling:

  • Regulatory compliance or model explainability (e.g., for banking regulation or audit) is critical.
  • You want simplicity, transparency, and justification via p-values and odds ratios.
  • Model performance is already excellent and interpretable features are a priority.

In [38]:
def evaluate_model_metrics(y_true, y_pred_prob):
    # Compute AUC
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_pred_prob)
    
    # Compute Gini
    gini = 2 * auc - 1

    # Compute ROC curve
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_prob)

    # Compute KS statistic
    ks = max(tpr - fpr)

    print(f"AUC-ROC Score: {auc:.4f}")
    print(f"Gini Coefficient: {gini:.4f}")
    print(f"KS Statistic: {ks:.4f}")

    # Plot ROC Curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'AUC = {auc:.4f}')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.legend()

    # Plot KS Curve
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(thresholds, tpr, label='TPR (Sensitivity)')
    plt.plot(thresholds, fpr, label='FPR (1 - Specificity)')
    plt.plot(thresholds, tpr - fpr, label=f'KS = {ks:.4f}', color='red', linestyle='--')
    plt.title('KS Curve')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.ylabel('Rate')
    plt.legend()

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    return auc, gini, ks

# y_true = true labels (0 = no default, 1 = default)
# y_pred_prob = predicted probabilities from logistic regression model

KS Statistic: 0.9594
Out[39]:
(0.9977709115436141, 0.9955418230872282, 0.9593516996730782)

Interpretations:¶

These results indicate that the logistic regression model performs exceptionally well in predicting credit risk (i.e., Probability of Default). Here's how to interpret each metric:

1. AUC-ROC Score = 0.9978¶

  • Meaning: The model can distinguish between defaulters and non-defaulters with 99.78% accuracy in terms of ranking by predicted probability.
  • Interpretation: Nearly perfect. AUC above 0.90 is generally considered excellent; 0.9978 is outstanding and rare.

2. Gini Coefficient = 0.9956¶

  • Formula: Gini = 2 * AUC - 1
  • Interpretation: Gini is a measure of predictive power used commonly in credit scoring.
    • Range: 0 (no discrimination) to 1 (perfect).
    • 0.9956 → Extremely high discriminatory power.
  • Usage: Widely used in banking/credit risk—your model is nearly perfect in separating good vs. bad borrowers.

3. Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) Statistic = 0.9599¶

  • Definition: Measures the maximum distance between the cumulative distributions of good and bad borrowers.
  • Interpretation:
    • KS > 0.40 is considered very strong in credit scoring.
    • Your KS of 0.9599 means the model separates classes exceptionally well.
    • This is usually the priority metric in credit risk modeling—you’ve achieved nearly the best possible.

Conclusion:¶

The logistic regression model is very likely production-ready from a performance standpoint. If business rules, regulatory constraints, or explainability matter (they often do in credit risk), logistic regression with these metrics is an excellent final model choice.

Export the regression model to a 'SAV' file with file name 'pd_model.sav'¶

import pickle
pickle.dump(reg1, open('C:/Disc D/365DataScience/Credit risk modeling/Data/pd_model.sav', 'wb'))
# Here we export our model to a 'SAV' file with file name 'pd_model.sav'.

E. Applying the PD Model¶

Calculating PD of individual accounts¶

Creating a Scorecard¶

To translate the outputs of the logistic regression model into an interpretable and operational credit scoring system, a scorecard is developed with a score range scaled between 300 and 850. Each categorical variable used in the logistic regression model is assigned a partial score based on its corresponding Weight of Evidence (WoE) and model coefficient. These partial scores reflect the contribution of each variable's category to the overall credit risk, and are linearly scaled so that the total score lies within the desired score range. This approach enables financial institutions to assess the creditworthiness of applicants in a transparent and standardized manner, facilitating consistent credit decisions across portfolios.

df_scorecard.loc[0, 'Score - Calculation'] = ((df_scorecard.loc[0, 'Coefficients'] - min_sum_coef) / 
                                              (max_sum_coef - min_sum_coef)) * (max_score - min_score) + min_score
# We divide the difference of the value of the 'Coefficients' column and the minimum sum of coefficients by
# the difference of the maximum sum of coefficients and the minimum sum of coefficients.
# Then, we multiply that by the difference between the maximum score and the minimum score.
# Then, we add minimum score.

# Aggregates the data in the 'Coefficients' column, calculating their minimum.

Caclulating Credit Score¶

In this section, we compute the final credit score for each borrower by aggregating the individual scores derived from each predictive variable included in the scorecard. Using the logistic regression model's coefficients and the Weight of Evidence (WoE) values associated with each variable category, we assign a score contribution to every relevant feature of a borrower's profile. These contributions are then summed and scaled to fall within the defined score range of 300 to 850, where a higher score indicates lower credit risk. This scoring process allows for the systematic evaluation of borrower risk, enabling more objective and data-driven lending decisions.

We need now the train and test datasets with reference categories

From Credit Score to PD¶

In this section, we translate the calculated credit scores into estimated probabilities of default (PD). While credit scores provide a relative ranking of borrower risk, mapping these scores to PD values enables a more quantitative and actionable risk assessment. By leveraging the inverse of the logistic function and the parameters derived from the logistic regression model, we can convert each borrower’s score into a corresponding PD. This transformation is crucial for aligning credit scoring with risk-based decision-making frameworks used in financial institutions, including provisioning, capital adequacy, and pricing strategies.

In [78]:
sum_coef_from_score = ((y_scores - min_score) / (max_score - min_score)) * (max_sum_coef - min_sum_coef) + min_sum_coef
# We divide the difference between the scores and the minimum score by
# the difference between the maximum score and the minimum score.
# Then, we multiply that by the difference between the maximum sum of coefficients and the minimum sum of coefficients.
# Then, we add the minimum sum of coefficients.
In [79]:
y_hat_proba_from_score = np.exp(sum_coef_from_score) / (np.exp(sum_coef_from_score) + 1)
# Here we divide an exponent raised to sum of coefficients from score by
# an exponent raised to sum of coefficients from score plus one.
y_hat_proba_from_score.head()
Out[79]:
0

1254829 0.009852
1859442 0.999979
337552 0.000040
1066533 0.000382

Setting Cut-offs¶

In this section, we establish scorecard cut-off values to support loan acceptance decisions. These cut-offs define the minimum credit score a borrower must achieve to qualify for credit approval. By mapping score thresholds to predicted probabilities of default (PD), lenders can align acceptance criteria with their risk appetite, regulatory standards, and portfolio performance targets. This ensures that credit decisions are not only consistent and transparent but also optimized to balance growth and risk mitigation.

df_cutoffs.loc[0, 'thresholds'] = 1 - 1 / np.power(10, 16)
# Let the first threshold (the value of the thresholds column with index 0) be equal to a number, very close to 1
# but smaller than 1, say 1 - 1 / 10 ^ 16.
In [91]:
df_cutoffs['Score'] = ((np.log(df_cutoffs['thresholds'] / (1 - df_cutoffs['thresholds'])) - min_sum_coef) * 
                       ((max_score - min_score) / (max_sum_coef - min_sum_coef)) + min_score).round()
# The score corresponsing to each threshold equals:
# The the difference between the natural logarithm of the ratio of the threshold and 1 minus the threshold and
# the minimum sum of coefficients
# multiplied by
# the sum of the minimum score and the ratio of the difference between the maximum score and minimum score and 
# the difference between the maximum sum of coefficients and the minimum sum of coefficients.

In [96]:
# We define a function called 'n_approved' which assigns a value of 1 if a predicted probability
# is greater than the parameter p, which is a threshold, and a value of 0, if it is not.
# Then it sums the column.
# Thus, if given any percentage values, the function will return
# the number of rows wih estimated probabilites greater than the threshold. 
def n_approved(p):
    return np.where(df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_proba'] >= p, 1, 0).sum()
In [97]:
df_cutoffs['N Approved'] = df_cutoffs['thresholds'].apply(n_approved)
# Assuming that all credit applications above a given probability of being 'good' will be approved,
# when we apply the 'n_approved' function to a threshold, it will return the number of approved applications.
# Thus, here we calculate the number of approved appliations for al thresholds.
df_cutoffs['N Rejected'] = df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_proba'].shape[0] - df_cutoffs['N Approved']
# Then, we calculate the number of rejected applications for each threshold.
# It is the difference between the total number of applications and the approved applications for that threshold.
df_cutoffs['Approval Rate'] = df_cutoffs['N Approved'] / df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_proba'].shape[0]
# Approval rate equalts the ratio of the approved applications and all applications.
df_cutoffs['Rejection Rate'] = 1 - df_cutoffs['Approval Rate']
# Rejection rate equals one minus approval rate.

To derive actionable insights for loan acceptance cut-off decisions, the most informative curve to plot is the Approval Rate vs. Credit Score. Additionally, PD (or 1 - TPR) vs. Score or FPR vs. Score can provide risk-based perspectives.

1. Approval Rate vs. Score¶

Purpose: Understand how loosening or tightening the credit score cut-off affects the proportion of applicants approved.

  • X-axis: Score
  • Y-axis: Approval Rate
  • Insight: Helps determine at what score the acceptance rate starts to climb significantly — ideal for setting thresholds aligned with your organization's target approval rate.

2. FPR and TPR vs. Score (Dual-Axis Curve)¶

Purpose: Assess the trade-off between approving good borrowers (TPR) and mistakenly approving risky ones (FPR).

  • X-axis: Score
  • Y-axis (left): TPR (True Positive Rate)
  • Y-axis (right): FPR (False Positive Rate)
  • Insight: Enables identification of score ranges where risk increases disproportionately compared to gain in good borrower approvals.

3. Score vs. Threshold or Score vs. PD¶

Purpose: Show how predicted risk or threshold maps to score.

  • If you already mapped PD to score, then plotting Score vs. PD allows you to define cut-offs based on a max acceptable PD.
  • Thresholds can also be plotted directly vs. score if they were calculated from predicted probabilities.

Common Strategies to Set the Optimal Cutoff: Maximize the KS Statistic¶

The KS (Kolmogorov–Smirnov) statistic helps identify the score where the separation between good and bad borrowers is greatest.

In [102]:
optimal_idx = df_cutoffs['tpr'] - df_cutoffs['fpr']
best_cutoff_index = optimal_idx.idxmax()
optimal_score = df_cutoffs.loc[best_cutoff_index, 'Score']
print(f"Optimal Cutoff Score (by max KS): {optimal_score}")

Optimal Cutoff Score (by max KS): 459.0

We found a cutoff score of 464.

In [103]:
# Add synthetic PD values for demonstration (replace with your actual PD if available)
# Here, we assume PD decreases with score
df_cutoffs['PD'] = 1 - df_cutoffs['Score'] / 850  # simplistic example

# Define cutoff scores and score bin ranges
cutoff_scores = [550, 600, 650, 700]
score_bins = {
    "Very Poor": (300, 579),
    "Fair": (580, 669),
    "Good": (670, 739),
    "Very Good": (740, 799),
    "Excellent": (800, 850),
}

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))

# Plot metrics
plt.plot(df_cutoffs['Score'], df_cutoffs['Approval Rate'], label='Approval Rate', color='blue', linewidth=2)
plt.plot(df_cutoffs['Score'], df_cutoffs['Rejection Rate'], label='Rejection Rate', color='orange', linewidth=2)
plt.plot(df_cutoffs['Score'], df_cutoffs['tpr'], label='TPR (Recall)', color='green', linewidth=2)
plt.plot(df_cutoffs['Score'], df_cutoffs['fpr'], label='FPR', color='red', linewidth=2)
plt.plot(df_cutoffs['Score'], df_cutoffs['PD'], label='PD (Estimated)', color='purple', linewidth=2, linestyle='--')

# Annotate cutoff points
for score in cutoff_scores:
    idx = (df_cutoffs['Score'] - score).abs().idxmin()
    score_val = df_cutoffs.loc[idx, 'Score']
    approval = df_cutoffs.loc[idx, 'Approval Rate']
    rejection = df_cutoffs.loc[idx, 'Rejection Rate']
    tpr = df_cutoffs.loc[idx, 'tpr']
    fpr = df_cutoffs.loc[idx, 'fpr']
    pd = df_cutoffs.loc[idx, 'PD']

    plt.axvline(x=score_val, color='gray', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
    plt.scatter(score_val, approval, color='blue')
    plt.scatter(score_val, rejection, color='orange')
    plt.scatter(score_val, tpr, color='green')
    plt.scatter(score_val, fpr, color='red')
    plt.scatter(score_val, pd, color='purple')

    plt.text(score_val - 5, max(approval, tpr) + 0.02,
             f"{int(score_val)}\nPD: {pd:.1%}\nApp: {approval:.1%}\nRej: {rejection:.1%}\nTPR: {tpr:.1%}\nFPR: {fpr:.1%}",
             fontsize=9, color='black', ha='right',
             bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.3', facecolor='white', edgecolor='gray'))

# Add shaded score bins
for label, (start, end) in score_bins.items():
    plt.axvspan(start, end, alpha=0.08, label=label, color='green')

plt.axvline(x=optimal_score, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label=f'Optimal Cutoff: {int(optimal_score)}')

# Final plot settings
plt.xlabel('Credit Score')
plt.ylabel('Rate / PD')
plt.title('Credit Score Insights: Approval, Rejection, PD, and Model Metrics')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.gca().invert_xaxis()  # Optional: Higher scores to the left
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Cutoff Score Interpretation (Score = 554)¶

  • Probability of Default (PD) 34.8%: This means that among borrowers approved with scores ≥554, approximately 1 in 3 are expected to default. This is relatively high credit risk.
  • Approval Rate 17.6%: Only 17.6% of all applicants are approved at this cutoff. This is a strict acceptance policy, aimed at reducing risk.
  • Rejection Rate 82.4%: A large portion of applicants are rejected, reflecting conservative risk appetite.
  • True Positive Rate (TPR) / Recall 82.1%: The model correctly identifies 82.1% of the actual defaulters — very strong recall performance.
  • False Positive Rate (FPR) 0.0%: No good applicants are mistakenly classified as risky — this suggests perfect precision at this cutoff.

Insights and Policy Implications¶

  • Risk-Control Trade-off:

The score of 554 captures most defaulters (TPR = 82.1%) while maintaining zero FPR, meaning it avoids lending to risky borrowers with high accuracy.

  • Very Conservative:

Since the approval rate is only 17.6%, many potentially creditworthy applicants may be excluded. This could affect business growth unless offset by very low losses.

  • High PD:

A PD of 34.8% in the approved segment is a concern — even among accepted applicants, default risk remains high, suggesting the model might need stronger segmentation or further score calibration.

Conclusion¶

  • If the goal is strict risk containment, a score cutoff of 554 is very effective: high recall and no false positives.
  • However, if growth or financial inclusion is also a goal, a higher cutoff (e.g., 620–650) might reduce PD while improving approval rates.
  • Consider using this score in a manual review zone rather than automatic approval.

Scoring Policy – Bullet Format¶

  • Score ≥ 720:
    • Approve Automatically (Low PD (<2%), strong creditworthiness).
    • Borrowers in this range show very low risk (PD < 2%), and approval rates are high with minimal false positives.
  • Score between 620 and 720:
    • Manual Review (Medium PD (2–10%), further evaluation recommended).
    • Medium-risk group; requires additional verification or compensating factors (e.g., collateral, employment status).
  • Score < 620:
    • Reject (High PD (>10%), likely to default).
    • High default risk (PD > 10%). Applications should not be approved unless exceptional circumstances apply.

Population Stability Index: Calculation and Interpretation¶

The file lending_club_clean.feather is a cleaned version of the Lending Club dataset, typically used for credit risk modeling and machine learning projects. It originates from the Lending Club loan data, which includes detailed information about personal loans issued over multiple years between 2007 and 2020.

Read the dataset and convert it to a csv file¶

# Chek if there are feature differences between the original dataset and the 2019 and 2020 year dataset
diff_items = list(set(list_2018).symmetric_difference(set(list_2020_19)))
print(diff_items)

['settlement_date', 'debt_settlement_flag_date', 'issue_d_date', 'settlement_status', 'sec_app_mths_since_last_major_derog', 'settlement_percentage', 'desc', 'member_id', 'settlement_term', 'settlement_amount', 'disbursement_method']

The unique diffrence is that the feature 'disbursement_method' is omitted, the other features are all ready dropped from the original dataset used for training and testing the PD model. The categorical features derived from the feature are also dropped from the final model with the other variables that are not significant with the p-value method.

In [159]:
# Save the dataframe : df_2019_2020 to a local csv file
df_2019_2020.to_csv('C:/Disc D/365DataScience/Credit risk modeling/Data2020/loan_data_2019_20.csv', index=False)

In the 2019–2020 data, the vast majority of loans (~85.9%) have 'loan_status' = 'Current', which means:

  • They haven’t reached maturity yet or are still in repayment.
  • You don’t know their final performance (whether they’ll eventually default or repay).

The original model excluded 'Current' because they are not resolved outcomes, which is good modeling practice.

Drop 'Current' and 'In Grace Period' from the 2019–2020 data, this ensures:

  • We're comparing like-for-like populations (resolved loans only).
  • Our PSI is based on loans with known final outcomes, keeping your analysis clean.

Loading the preprocessed, engineered and categorized dataset for 2019 and 2020¶

# We remove the rows with values in the 'index' column 'Intercept' and 'Score'.
In [499]:
# Make sure to replace 0 values with a small number to avoid division by zero
PSI_calc['Proportions_Train'] = PSI_calc['Proportions_Train'].replace(0, 1e-6)
PSI_calc['Proportions_New'] = PSI_calc['Proportions_New'].replace(0, 1e-6)

PSI_calc['Contribution'] = np.where((PSI_calc['Proportions_Train'] == 0) | (PSI_calc['Proportions_New'] == 0), 0, 
                 (PSI_calc['Proportions_New'] - PSI_calc['Proportions_Train']) * np.log(PSI_calc['Proportions_New'] / PSI_calc['Proportions_Train']))
# We calculate the contribution of each dummy variable to the PSI of each original variable it comes from.
# If either the proportion of old data or the proportion of new data are 0, the contribution is 0.
# Otherwise, we apply the PSI formula for each contribution.

Interpretations:¶

The Population Stability Index (PSI) results — they give a great overview of how much each feature's distribution has changed between the training and scoring datasets. Here's how to interpret the PSI values and identify which features might warrant further investigation or action.

PSI Interpretation Guidelines¶

As a rule of thumb:

  • < 0.1 : No significant shift ---- Feature is stable
  • 0.1 – 0.25 : Moderate shift ---- Monitor or adjust model
  • > 0.25 : Significant shift ---- Likely requires remediation

Stable Features (PSI < 0.1)¶

Most features fall into this category — this is good. For example:

  • addr_state: 0.0016
  • emp_length_int: 0.0117
  • fico_range_high: 0.139 — borderline stable
  • home_ownership: 0.0046
  • loan_amnt: 0.0427
  • debt_settlement_flag: 0.0188

...and many more.

You likely don’t need to act on these unless you're doing long-term monitoring or spot domain-specific anomalies.

Moderate Shift (0.1 < PSI < 0.25)¶

Features in this range could introduce some drift, depending on model sensitivity:

  • bc_open_to_buy: 0.133
  • verification_status: 0.172
  • revol_bal_to_bc_limit: 0.175
  • total_cu_tl: 0.169
  • percent_bc_gt_75: 0.206
  • principal_paid_ratio: 0.245
  • open_il_12m: 0.223
  • open_rv_12m: 0.249

→ These features may need recalibration or additional regularization.

Significant Shift (PSI > 0.25)¶

These are red flags and may impact model performance if left unchanged:

  • grade : 0.288
  • initial_list_status : 0.524
  • inq_last_12m : 0.822
  • int_rate : 4.191
  • last_pymnt_amnt : 0.209
  • max_bal_bc : 2.023
  • min_mths_since_delinquency : 6.589
  • months_since_last_credit_pull : 4.264
  • mths_since_rcnt_il : 8.185
  • mths_since_recent_inq : 1.512
  • mths_since_recent_revol_delinq : 1.375

These features have significantly shifted in distribution and are likely no longer reliable in your model without adjustment.

In Loss Given Default (LGD) modeling, it is essential to consider only the accounts that have been charged-off (written-off) because LGD represents the proportion of the exposure that is not recovered once a borrower defaults. Charged-off accounts are those where the lender has formally recognized the loan as uncollectible, making them the true realizations of default events. Including accounts that have not been written-off—such as those still in early delinquency or recovery—would introduce noise and uncertainty, as their final loss outcomes are unknown or incomplete. By focusing solely on charged-off accounts, the model is trained on finalized loss data, ensuring more accurate estimation of recovery rates and the actual economic loss associated with default.

2. Dependent Variables¶

In [389]:
# 1. Identify defaulted loans
# Common default statuses in Lending Club data
default_statuses = ['Charged Off', 'Default', 'Does not meet the credit policy. Status:Charged Off']
loan_data_07_18['is_default'] = loan_data_07_18['loan_status'].isin(default_statuses)

# 2. Ensure relevant columns exist and are numeric
# 'recoveries' is the total recovered amount from defaulted loans
# 'funded_amnt' or 'funded_amnt_inv' can be used as a proxy for EAD (Exposure at Default)
loan_data_07_18['recoveries'] = pd.to_numeric(loan_data_07_18['recoveries'], errors='coerce').fillna(0)
loan_data_07_18['funded_amnt'] = pd.to_numeric(loan_data_07_18['funded_amnt'], errors='coerce')

# ===========3. Compute Recovery Rate====================================
# By default set to 0
loan_data_07_18['recovery_rate'] = 0.0

# For defaulted loans, compute Recovery Rate = recoveries / funded_amnt (EAD)
mask_default = loan_data_07_18['is_default'] & (loan_data_07_18['funded_amnt'] > 0)
loan_data_07_18.loc[mask_default, 'recovery_rate'] = loan_data_07_18.loc[mask_default, 'recoveries'] / loan_data_07_18.loc[mask_default, 'funded_amnt']

# Optional: clip to [0, 1] range
loan_data_07_18['recovery_rate'] = loan_data_07_18['recovery_rate'].clip(lower=0, upper=1)

# ==============4. Binary Recovery Indicator=============================
# 1 if recovery > 0
# 0 if recovery == 0 (even if loan defaulted)
# 0 also for non-defaulted loans, since they didn’t go through recovery
loan_data_07_18['recovery_rate_0_1'] = 0.0
loan_data_07_18.loc[loan_data_07_18['is_default'] & (loan_data_07_18['recovery_rate'] > 0), 'recovery_rate_0_1'] = 1

# =============5. Credit Conversion Factor (CCF)=========================
# For defaulted loans → compute normally
# For non-defaulted loans → set CCF = 0, as no additional drawdown occurred
loan_data_07_18['CCF'] = 0.0
loan_data_07_18.loc[loan_data_07_18['is_default'], 'CCF'] = (
    (loan_data_07_18.loc[loan_data_07_18['is_default'], 'funded_amnt'] - 
     loan_data_07_18.loc[loan_data_07_18['is_default'], 'total_rec_prncp']) /
    loan_data_07_18.loc[loan_data_07_18['is_default'], 'funded_amnt']
).astype(float)

4. LGD model: Stage 1 - Classification¶

  • Objective: Predict whether recovery occurs.
  • Target: recovery_rate_class:
    • 0 if recovery_rate == 0
    • 1 if recovery_rate > 0
  • Model: Classifier (e.g., LightGBMClassifier).
  • Prediction: Binary prediction (0 or 1) or probability (P(recovery > 0)).

Logistic Regression model¶

Train the LR model¶

In [235]:
reg_lgd_st_1 = LogisticRegression_with_p_values()
# We create an instance of an object from the 'LogisticRegression' class.
reg_lgd_st_1.fit(X_inputs_stage1_train, y_stage1_train)
# Estimates the coefficients of the object from the 'LogisticRegression' class
# with inputs (independent variables) contained in the first dataframe
# and targets (dependent variables) contained in the second dataframe.
In [236]:
feature_name = X_inputs_stage1_train.columns.values
# Stores the names of the columns of a dataframe in a variable.
In [237]:
summary_table = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Feature name'], data = feature_name)
# Creates a dataframe with a column titled 'Feature name' and row values contained in the 'feature_name' variable.
summary_table['Coefficients'] = np.transpose(reg_lgd_st_1.coef_)
# Creates a new column in the dataframe, called 'Coefficients',
# with row values the transposed coefficients from the 'LogisticRegression' object.
summary_table.index = summary_table.index + 1
# Increases the index of every row of the dataframe with 1.
summary_table.loc[0] = ['Intercept', reg_lgd_st_1.intercept_[0]]
# Assigns values of the row with index 0 of the dataframe.
summary_table = summary_table.sort_index()
# Sorts the dataframe by index.
p_values = reg_lgd_st_1.p_values
# We take the result of the newly added method 'p_values' and store it in a variable 'p_values'.
p_values = np.append(np.nan,np.array(p_values))
# We add the value 'NaN' in the beginning of the variable with p-values.
summary_table['p_values'] = p_values
# In the 'summary_table' dataframe, we add a new column, called 'p_values', containing the values from the 'p_values' variable.

Estimating the Аccuracy of the Мodel¶

In [251]:
tr = 0.5
# We create a new column with an indicator,
# where every observation that has predicted probability greater than the threshold has a value of 1,
# and every observation that has predicted probability lower than the threshold has a value of 0.
df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_lgd_stage1'] = np.where(df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_proba_lgd_stage1'] > tr, 1, 0)

# Creates a cross-table where the actual values are displayed by rows and the predicted values by columns.
# This table is known as a Confusion Matrix.

In [162]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score
In [256]:
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(df_actual_predicted_probs['y_test_lgd_stage1'], df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_proba_lgd_stage1'])
# Returns the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve from a set of actual values and their predicted probabilities.
# As a result, we get three arrays: the false positive rates, the true positive rates, and the thresholds.
# we store each of the three arrays in a separate variable.
In [164]:
plt.plot(fpr, tpr)
# We plot the false positive rate along the x-axis and the true positive rate along the y-axis,
# thus plotting the ROC curve.
plt.plot(fpr, fpr, linestyle = '--', color = 'k')
# We plot a seconary diagonal line, with dashed line style and black color.
plt.xlabel('False positive rate')
# We name the x-axis "False positive rate".
plt.ylabel('True positive rate')
# We name the x-axis "True positive rate".
plt.title('ROC curve')
# We name the graph "ROC curve".
Out[164]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'ROC curve')
In [165]:
AUROC = roc_auc_score(df_actual_predicted_probs['y_test_lgd_stage1'], df_actual_predicted_probs['y_hat_test_proba_lgd_stage1'])
# Calculates the Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (AUROC)
# from a set of actual values and their predicted probabilities.
AUROC
Out[165]:
0.7826943246137026

Interpretations¶

Confusion Matrix

  • TN (True Negatives): Model correctly predicted 0 LGD (no loss).
  • FP (False Positives): Model predicted 1 (LGD event), but it was actually 0.
  • FN (False Negatives): Model predicted 0, but it was actually a charged-off account with loss.
  • TP (True Positives): Model correctly predicted LGD (loss event).

UROC = 0.7827

  • AUROC (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve) measures the model's ability to distinguish between classes.
  • 0.78 is considered good — it means the model correctly ranks a randomly chosen positive case higher than a negative case about 78% of the time. AUROC shows then good discriminatory power, meaning the model is effective at distinguishing high-loss vs low-loss accounts.

Business Interpretation:

  • The model is more likely to err on the safe side (predict LGD when it's not), which can be acceptable in credit risk if the cost of underestimating losses is high.

Comparison of diffrent models¶

Evaluation Criteria:¶

We specified recall and AUC-ROC as priority metrics — these are highly appropriate for credit risk modeling, especially:

  • Recall (on class 1): Important to identify most of the defaults.
  • AUC-ROC: Measures the model's overall ability to separate the two classes.

Logistic Regression:¶

  • Recall (1) = 0.8586
  • AUC-ROC = 0.7827
  • Accuracy = 0.7335
  • Precision (1) = 0.7772
  • F1 Score (1) = 0.8159

Random Forest:¶

  • Recall (1) = 0.6482
  • AUC-ROC = 0.8058
  • Accuracy = 0.7031
  • Precision (1) = 0.8902
  • F1 Score (1) = 0.7502

XGBoost:¶

  • Recall (1) = 0.8638
  • AUC-ROC = 0.8257
  • Accuracy = 0.7593
  • Precision (1) = 0.8016
  • F1 Score (1) = 0.8315

LightGBM:¶

  • Recall (1) = 0.8738
  • AUC-ROC = 0.8252
  • Accuracy = 0.7583
  • Precision (1) = 0.7950
  • F1 Score (1) = 0.8326

Key Insights¶

  • 1. Recall (priority):

    • LightGBM performs best (0.8738), slightly above XGBoost (0.8638) and Logistic Regression (0.8586).
    • Random Forest lags behind significantly (0.6482).

  • 2. AUC-ROC (priority):

    • XGBoost (0.8257) and LightGBM (0.8252) are neck and neck at the top.
    • Random Forest scores well (0.8058) but has worse recall.
    • Logistic Regression underperforms here (0.7827).

  • 3. Overall performance (Accuracy, Precision, F1):

    • XGBoost and LightGBM offer balanced performance across all metrics.
    • Logistic Regression is strong but less powerful in ROC space.
    • Random Forest is over-precise, but under-recalls, suggesting it's overconfident about positive predictions.

Final Recommendation: Retain the LightGBM Model¶

  • Why LightGBM?
    • Best recall (crucial for default detection).
    • Excellent AUC-ROC (0.8252).
    • Best F1 score (0.8326), indicating strong balance between precision and recall.
    • Efficient and fast for deployment.
    • Slightly more consistent than XGBoost across all metrics.

5. LGD model: Stage 2 - Regression¶

  • Objective: Estimate actual recovery rate.
  • Target: recovery_rate ∈ (0, 1].
  • Model: Regressor (e.g., LightGBMRegressor).
  • Training Data: Only samples where recovery_rate > 0.
  • Prediction: Recovery rate for those predicted as class 1 in stage 1.

Data preparation¶

In [258]:
lgd_stage_2_data = loan_data_defaults[loan_data_defaults['recovery_rate_0_1'] == 1]
# Here we take only rows where the original recovery rate variable is greater than 0,
# i.e. where the indicator variable we created is equal to 1.
In [260]:
# LGD model stage 2 datasets: how much more than 0 is the recovery rate
lgd_inputs_stage_2_train, lgd_inputs_stage_2_test, lgd_targets_stage_2_train, lgd_targets_stage_2_test = train_test_split(lgd_stage_2_data,
                                                     lgd_stage_2_data['recovery_rate'], test_size = 0.2, random_state = 42)
# Takes a set of inputs and a set of targets as arguments. Splits the inputs and the targets into four dataframes:
# Inputs - Train, Inputs - Test, Targets - Train, Targets - Test.
In [261]:
# Here we keep only the variables we need for the model.

Linear Regression model¶

Definition of a class for linear regression¶

In [298]:
# P values for sklearn logistic regression.
# Class to display p-values for linear regression in sklearn.
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats as stat
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

class MyLinearRegression_with_p_values:
    
    def __init__(self,*args,**kwargs):
        self.model = linear_model.LinearRegression(*args,**kwargs)

    def fit(self, X, y):
        self.model.fit(X, y)
        self.coef_ = self.model.coef_
        self.intercept_ = self.model.intercept_
        # Compute residuals
        y_pred = self.model.predict(X)
        residuals = y - y_pred
        # Degrees of freedom
        dof = X.shape[0] - X.shape[1]
        # Mean squared error
        mse = np.sum(residuals ** 2) / dof
        # Covariance matrix (using pseudo-inverse for safety)
        cov_matrix = np.linalg.pinv(X.T @ X)
        # Standard errors
        se = np.sqrt(np.diag(mse * cov_matrix))
        # t-statistics and p-values
        self.t = self.coef_ / se
        self.p = 2 * (1 - stat.t.cdf(np.abs(self.t), df=dof))
        return self
    
 # Predict methods
    def predict(self, X):
        return self.model.predict(X)

Evaluation of the linear regression model¶

In [333]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

### targets prediction
y_pred = reg_lgd_st_2.predict(X_inputs_stage2_test)
y_true = y_stage2_test

# Evaluate the metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)

print(f"MSE: {mse:.6f}")
print(f"RMSE: {rmse:.6f}")
print(f"MAE: {mae:.6f}")
print(f"R²: {r2:.6f}")

MSE: 0.007009
RMSE: 0.083720
MAE: 0.047884
R²: 0.247034

The metrics suggest:

  • MSE = 0.007009 and RMSE = 0.0837 means on average your model's predictions deviate from actual values by about 0.084 (in the target's unit).
  • MAE = 0.0479 shows the average absolute error, which is less sensitive to outliers than RMSE.
  • R² = 0.247 means the model explains roughly 24.7% of the variance in the targets, which is moderate but leaves plenty of room for improvement.

What does this mean in practice?

  • The model has some predictive power, but a large part of the variation remains unexplained.
  • This is typical for noisy or complex data where a simple linear model can only capture linear relationships.

XGBoost Hyperparameter Tuning¶

In [343]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

X_train_st2 = X_inputs_stage2_train
X_test_st2 = X_inputs_stage2_test
y_train_st2 = y_stage2_train
y_test_st2 = y_stage2_test

# rename the columns
X_train_st2.columns = X_train_st2.columns.str.replace(r"[\[\]<>]", "", regex=True)
X_test_st2.columns = X_test_st2.columns.str.replace(r"[\[\]<>]", "", regex=True)

X_train_st2 = X_train_st2.copy()
y_train_st2 = y_train_st2.copy()

# Define the parameter grid
xgb_param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7, 10],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2],
    'subsample': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'colsample_bytree': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'reg_alpha': [0, 0.01, 0.1],
    'reg_lambda': [1, 1.5, 2]
}

# Initialize the model
xgb = XGBRegressor(random_state=42)

# Setup Randomized Search
xgb_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=xgb,
    param_distributions=xgb_param_grid,
    n_iter=30,  # Try 30 combinations
    scoring='r2',
    cv=5,
    verbose=1,
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=1
)

# Fit to the training data
xgb_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best estimator and score
print("Best XGBoost Parameters:", xgb_search.best_params_)
print("Best XGBoost CV R² Score:", xgb_search.best_score_)

# Evaluate on test set
best_xgb = xgb_search.best_estimator_
xgb_preds_tuned = best_xgb.predict(X_test)

mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, xgb_preds_tuned)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, xgb_preds_tuned)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, xgb_preds_tuned)

print(f"Tuned XGBoost MSE: {mse:.6f}")
print(f"Tuned XGBoost RMSE: {rmse:.6f}")
print(f"Tuned XGBoost MAE: {mae:.6f}")
print(f"Tuned XGBoost R²: {r2:.6f}")

    df.columns = df.columns.str.replace(r"[^\w]", "_", regex=True)

LightGBM Hyperparameter Tuning¶

In [346]:
X_train_lgb = X_train_lgb.copy()
y_train = y_train.copy()

# Define the base model
lgbm = LGBMRegressor(random_state=42)

# Define hyperparameter space for tuning
lgbm_param_grid = {
    'num_leaves': [31, 50, 70, 100],
    'max_depth': [-1, 5, 10, 15],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2],
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'subsample': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'colsample_bytree': [0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'reg_alpha': [0.0, 0.1, 0.5],
    'reg_lambda': [0.0, 1.0, 1.5]
}

# Setup RandomizedSearchCV
lgbm_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=lgbm,
    param_distributions=lgbm_param_grid,
    n_iter=30,
    scoring='r2',
    cv=5,
    verbose=1,
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=1
)

# Fit the search object
lgbm_search.fit(X_train_lgb, y_train)

# Get best model and predictions
best_lgbm = lgbm_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_lgb = best_lgbm.predict(X_test_lgb)

# Evaluate performance
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_lgb)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_lgb)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_lgb)

# Output results
print("Best LightGBM Parameters:", lgbm_search.best_params_)
print("Tuned LightGBM MSE:", mse)
print("Tuned LightGBM RMSE:", rmse)
print("Tuned LightGBM MAE:", mae)
print("Tuned LightGBM R²:", r2)

Model Performance Comparison¶

Linear Regression¶

  • MSE = 0.007009
  • RMSE = 0.083720
  • MAE = 0.047884
  • R² = 0.247034

Random Forest¶

  • MSE = 0.006499
  • RMSE = 0.080614
  • MAE = 0.042935
  • R² = 0.301856

Hist. Gradient Boosting¶

  • MSE = 0.006158
  • RMSE = 0.078475
  • MAE = 0.041755
  • R² = 0.338415

Tuned XGBoost¶

  • MSE = 0.006161
  • RMSE = 0.078492
  • MAE = 0.041761
  • R² = 0.338138

Tuned LightGBM¶

  • MSE = 0.006130
  • RMSE = 0.078294
  • MAE = 0.041440
  • R² = 0.341462

Interpretation¶

  • Tuned LightGBM is the best-performing model across all key metrics.
  • It slightly outperforms tuned XGBoost, and beats both Random Forest and HistGradientBoosting in R² and error metrics.
  • Compared to Linear Regression, the R² improved from 0.25 → 0.34, which is a significant boost in explanatory power.

Tuned LightGBM model¶

In [179]:
from sklearn.metrics import  mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score
from lightgbm import LGBMRegressor
import re

# Copying the dataframe
X_train_st2 = X_inputs_stage2_train
X_test_st2 = X_inputs_stage2_test
y_train_st2 = y_stage2_train
y_test_st2 = y_stage2_test

def clean_column_names(df):
    df.columns = df.columns.str.replace(r"[^\w]", "_", regex=True)
    return df

X_train_lgb = clean_column_names(X_train_st2)
X_test_lgb = clean_column_names(X_test_st2)

# 1. Define the best hyperparameters from tuning
best_params = {
    'subsample': 0.6, 
     'reg_lambda': 1.0, 
     'reg_alpha': 0.0, 
     'num_leaves': 100, 
     'n_estimators': 300, 
     'max_depth': -1, 
     'learning_rate': 0.05, 
     'colsample_bytree': 1.0,
     'random_state': 42
}

# Initialize and train LightGBM
tuned_lgb_model = LGBMRegressor(**best_params)
tuned_lgb_model.fit(X_train_lgb, y_train_st2)

# Predict
y_lgb_preds = tuned_lgb_model.predict(X_test_lgb)

# Metrics
lgb_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test_st2, y_lgb_preds)
lgb_rmse = np.sqrt(lgb_mse)
lgb_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test_st2, y_lgb_preds)
lgb_r2 = r2_score(y_test_st2, y_lgb_preds)

print(f"LightGBM MSE: {lgb_mse:.6f}")
print(f"LightGBM RMSE: {lgb_rmse:.6f}")
print(f"LightGBM MAE: {lgb_mae:.6f}")
print(f"LightGBM R²: {lgb_r2:.6f}")

[LightGBM] [Info] Auto-choosing row-wise multi-threading, the overhead of testing was 0.027248 seconds.
You can set `force_row_wise=true` to remove the overhead.
And if memory is not enough, you can set `force_col_wise=true`.

[LightGBM] [Info] Number of data points in the train set: 147747, number of used features: 147
[LightGBM] [Info] Start training from score 0.109545
LightGBM MSE: 0.006130
LightGBM RMSE: 0.078294
LightGBM MAE: 0.041440
LightGBM R²: 0.341462

6. Combining Stage 1 and 2: Predicted LGD¶

Two-Stage LGD Modeling: Predicting Loss Given Default¶

In [287]:
X_train_st1 = X_inputs_stage1_train

# Step 1: Predict class labels (binary: 0 or 1)
y_hat_test_stage1_label = LGBM_lgd_st_1.predict(X_test_st1)

# Step 2: Get indices where stage 1 predicts recovery (class 1)
stage2_indices = np.where(y_hat_test_stage1_label == 1)[0]

# Step 3: Select same rows from X_test_stage1 for regression
X_test_stage2_pred = X_test_stage1.iloc[stage2_indices]

# Step 4: Predict recovery rate for only those
y_hat_test_stage2 = tuned_lgb_model.predict(X_test_stage2_pred)

# Step 5: Initialize LGD predictions
final_LGD_pred = np.ones(len(X_test_st1))  # default LGD = 1

# Step 6: Update predictions where recovery was predicted
final_LGD_pred[stage2_indices] = 1 - y_hat_test_stage2

Evaluation of the Two-Stage LGD Model¶

In [288]:
from sklearn.metrics import root_mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

# Actual LGD from test data
recovery_rate_test = X_stage1_test['recovery_rate']
actual_LGD = 1 - recovery_rate_test

# Evaluation
rmse = rmse = root_mean_squared_error(actual_LGD, final_LGD_pred)
mae = mean_absolute_error(actual_LGD, final_LGD_pred)
r2 = r2_score(actual_LGD, final_LGD_pred)

print(f"Final Two-Stage LGD Model:")
print(f"RMSE: {rmse:.4f}")
print(f"MAE:  {mae:.4f}")
print(f"R²:   {r2:.4f}")

Final Two-Stage LGD Model:
RMSE: 0.0767
MAE:  0.0463
R²:   0.3438

Final Two-Stage LGD Model Evaluation:

  • RMSE = 0.0767: On average, your predicted LGD is about 7.67 percentage points away from the actual LGD values.
  • MAE = 0.0463: The average absolute error in your LGD predictions is 4.63 percentage points — very good for LGD modeling.
  • R² = 0.3438: Your model explains about 34.38% of the variance in LGD. For LGD prediction (a challenging task), this is a respectable baseline.

High-Level Observations¶

Extreme Coefficients:

  • Variables like principal_paid_ratio:*. and Intercept have massively large coefficients (~6.277e+10). This likely points to perfect multicollinearity or data leakage.
  • Similarly, out_prncp:>0 has an extreme negative coefficient. This is suspicious and likely also due to leakage, as it directly indicates payment progress.

P-values:

  • Many features (e.g., grade:A, term:60, last_pymnt_amnt:, fico_range_high:) are statistically significant (p < 0.05).
  • Several features have high p-values (e.g., verification_status:Not Verified, loan_amnt:2500-6500, inq_last_6mths:>=4), suggesting low explanatory power for those bins.

Multicollinearity:

  • Features with identical coefficients and p-values (e.g., all principal_paid_ratio:* have the same value) likely come from one-hot encoding with a constant target pattern, a major red flag.

Interpretation of Key Variables¶

Credit Risk-Related:

  • fico_range_high:* and last_fico_range_high:*. have strong negative coefficients, consistent with higher credit scores reducing LGD.
  • int_rate:*. has strong positive coefficients, consistent with higher interest rates being associated with riskier loans.

Payment Behavior:

  • last_pymnt_amnt:*. coefficients are strongly negative, which makes sense—more recent payment → lower LGD.
  • principal_paid_ratio:*: these are problematic (see below).

Loan & Borrower Attributes:

  • loan_amnt:*: Positive coefficients indicate larger loan size may be associated with higher LGD, consistent with expected behavior.
  • annual_inc:*: Not strongly significant across most bins. Income may have a nonlinear or interaction effect not captured well in linear models.

Loan Purpose:

  • purpose:debt_consolidation and purpose:credit_card have negative coefficients, possibly suggesting lower LGD, potentially due to better-defined loan use.

Flags for Potential Data Leakage or Modeling Errors:

  • principal_paid_ratio:*: All have the same massive coefficient and p-value = 0. Indicates data leakage or perfect separation.
  • out_prncp:>0 Target leakage — reveals payment status (and indirectly LGD). Should not be used in modeling.

Remove Potentially Leaky Features:¶

  • principal_paid_ratio
  • out_prncp
  • Possibly last_pymnt_amnt (if it occurs after LGD is measured)

Interpretation¶

The model evaluation results and correlation matrix indicate strong predictive performance.

Model Evaluation Metrics:¶

  • MSE (Mean Squared Error) = 0.005099: Indicates a low average squared error between predicted and actual values — lower is better.
  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) = 0.071405: A more interpretable version of MSE (in original units). A small RMSE shows good predictive accuracy.
  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error) = 0.058248: Low average magnitude of errors, showing that predictions are consistently close to actuals.
  • R² (R-squared) = 0.893746: Suggests that ~89.4% of the variance in the target variable is explained by the model — strong fit.

Conclusion: The model is performing well with low error metrics and high explanatory power.

Correlation Matrix:¶

  • The Pearson correlation between your model predictions (CCF) and the actual target variable (0) is 0.945, which is very high.
  • This reinforces that the model predictions are highly aligned with the actual values — a good sign of both linearity and predictive performance.

2. ExpectedLossPipeline Class¶

We’ll define a robust ExpectedLossPipeline class that:

  • Accepts models for PD, LGD (2-stage), and CCF
  • Computes EAD and EL
  • Handles default logic properly
In [363]:
class ExpectedLossPipeline:
    def __init__(self, pd_model, lgd_stage1_model, lgd_stage2_model, ccf_model):
        self.pd_model = pd_model
        self.lgd_stage1_model = lgd_stage1_model
        self.lgd_stage2_model = lgd_stage2_model
        self.ccf_model = ccf_model

    def predict_pd(self, X):
        return self.pd_model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]

    def predict_lgd(self, X, is_default):
        lgd_pred = pd.Series(0.0, index=X.index)
        default_idx = is_default[is_default].index

        if not default_idx.empty:
            stage1_preds = self.lgd_stage1_model.predict(X.loc[default_idx])
            valid_idx = default_idx[stage1_preds == 1]
            if not valid_idx.empty:
                lgd_pred.loc[valid_idx] = self.lgd_stage2_model.predict(X.loc[valid_idx])

        return lgd_pred

    def predict_ccf(self, X, is_default):
        ccf_pred = pd.Series(0.0, index=X.index)
        default_idx = is_default[is_default].index

        if not default_idx.empty:
            ccf_pred.loc[default_idx] = self.ccf_model.predict(X.loc[default_idx])

        return pd.Series(np.clip(ccf_pred, 0, 1), index=X.index)

    def predict_ead(self, ccf, funded_amnt):
        return ccf * funded_amnt

    def predict_el(self, X, funded_amnt, is_default):
        pd_pred = self.predict_pd(X)
        lgd_pred = self.predict_lgd(X, is_default)
        ccf_pred = self.predict_ccf(X, is_default)
        ead_pred = self.predict_ead(ccf_pred, funded_amnt)

        el = pd_pred * lgd_pred * ead_pred
        return pd.DataFrame({
            'PD': pd_pred,
            'LGD': lgd_pred,
            'CCF': ccf_pred,
            'EAD': ead_pred,
            'EL': el
        }, index=X.index)

Application to loan_data_07_18 dataset¶

# Start from a clean base DataFrame that includes all required columns
base_df = loan_data_07_18[['loan_status', 'funded_amnt'] + list_feat_to_consider].copy()

# Filter out rows with any missing values (to avoid alignment issues)
base_df.dropna(inplace=True)

# Define inputs based on the same index
X_loan_data = base_df[list_feat_to_consider]
funded_amnt = base_df['funded_amnt']
is_default = base_df['loan_status'].isin(['Charged Off', 'Default', 'Does not meet the credit policy. Status:Charged Off'])

# Instantiate the pipeline
el_pipeline = ExpectedLossPipeline(
    pd_model = reg1,
    lgd_stage1_model =  LGBM_lgd_st_1,
    lgd_stage2_model = tuned_lgb_model,
    ccf_model = reg_ead
)

# Predict EL and components
el_outputs = el_pipeline.predict_el(X_loan_data, funded_amnt, is_default)
